The government wants to limit the torture of "witches", published a brochure
Women who are declared witches in Burkina Faso have several characteristics in common.
Rather, they belong to the older generation, are unable to participate in work, for example, for health reasons, are free and do not have children.
The one who "becomes a witch" is sent to isolation so as not to threaten the rest of the village.
"This fate can only be achieved very seldom."
"Even young healthy women do not retire because they help with work and give birth to children," describes a nun who, in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso, is caring in a special house for more than a hundred women who have been expelled from their ranks by their community.
The local government has now decided to take action against the unusual "social measure".
She published an information booklet to help limit the witch hunt.
But the thing has a hook.
“More than 70 percent of adults in Burkina Faso are unable to read,” said Die Standard.
Accusations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, neighbouring Burkina Faso, a 72-year-old woman, Amma Hemmah, died last week after she was tortured by three women and two men, poured oil on her and set on fire.
The case was reported by the BBC.
The perpetrators say it was an unfortunate coincidence.
According to their version, an oil was lit on the woman, which is used for ritual anointing.
It was said to have burned after the group wanted to "throw out the evil spirit" from the woman.
Isolation of "witches" is supported by people regardless of the level of education achieved.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 24-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso as saying, “The devourers of human souls have always posed a danger,” he said.
While the government is trying to mitigate the witch hunt in Burkina Faso, the president himself took part in Gambia last year.
"Gambian President Jammi, after his aunt's death, launched an extensive hunt for witches who were supposed to participate in her death and try to kill the president himself with black magic."
"He summoned shamans from nearby Guinea who, accompanied by police, soldiers and the president's personal security, forcibly took randomly selected men and women from Gambian villages to the president's farm in Kanilai," Amnesty International said in a statement.
On the farm, imprisoned people had to drink herbal potions with hallucinogenic effects, which in addition caused intestinal and renal problems.
The two prisoners did not survive their stay on the farm.
After international pressure, nearly a thousand prisoners were finally released from prison.
