"This organism has a double capacity."
"It can grow either because of phosphorus or arsenic."
“This fact is very strange, but it’s not proof that it’s some form of really ‘extraterrestrial’ life,” said Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, a co-author of the report, which appeared Thursday in the online edition of Science.
For a long time, it was considered necessary for life six main elements - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
Scientists have found, however, that bacteria discovered in Mono Lake, California, are able to continue growing after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
“You’re starting to wonder what else is possible,” said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, a co-author of the report.
This finding is important for finding life outside of Earth because researchers need to be able to recognize life and know what life may look like, Anbar said.
The study focuses on microbes found on Earth.
However, a report on this novelty published to discuss it, which did not disclose the details of the finding, has sparked widespread speculation on the Internet that the report reveals the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
It's not like that.
The discovery “shows that other planetary organisms may be able to harness other elements that drive biochemistry, and that the set of elements we consider to be ‘standard’ may not be as absolutely essential to life,” said Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
"This work is unusual because it shows the replacement of one element by another element in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure," Cockell added.
It wasn't a random find.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Astrobiology Institute, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it exhibits high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically very similar elements, so she thought that a microbe exposed to both elements might be able to replace one after the other.
"Arzene is poisonous mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to phosphorus."
“As a result, it is very difficult for organisms to separate these elements from each other.”
"However, arsenic is so different that it doesn't work as well as phosphorus. When it gets into the body, it starts working in biochemical processes," Anbar explained.
Scientists collect bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and expose them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which bacteria are able to adapt and grow.
Microbes grow better under the influence of phosphorus, but since they can also survive with arsenic replacement, there is an increased possibility that a form of life that uses arsenic may occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea of arsenic, which could be replaced by phosphorus, is not new, but there has never been an example on which this fact could be proven.
Arzene was more common in earlier times on Earth, she said, and so scientists speculated that it could have been used by earlier life forms.
"This suggests there may have been other ways to create life, not just the way it was created in the early Earth period," said Foster, who was not part of the Wolfe-Simon research team.
