Ethics experts claim that Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were friends before the affair, appeared to be in violation of the ban on lobbying.
Evidence that was released "showed that this was a clear case of preparation for a violation of the law," said Stanley Brand, a Washington-based lawyer who specializes in advocating for clients who are being investigated by the government.
While Justice Department officials refused to explain the reasons for the decision in Senator Ensign's case, Mr. Brand and other lawyers specializing in ethics said that the Department is wary of political lawsuits, after a large number of failures, including last year's decision to sue the state for suing the defendant.
Federal prosecutors "clearly hid their weapons," said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a group of lawyers who filed several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
