Paul Coggins, Mr. Ensign's chief lawyer, said in an interview that the Attorney General's Office called him on Monday and then the next day, and told him that the department found no charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign's advocacy team is working with prosecutors to convince them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement Wednesday, "acted in accordance with the law."
Mr. Coggins refused to specify the legal arguments he had submitted to prosecutors.
