Pol Pot died a natural death in 1998 and Ta Mok, who endured, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the nearby Dangrek Mountains.
He died in Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Their patrons no longer cared about them, most of the former Khmer Rouge fighters descended into ordinary Cambodian rural life, and many of them nostalgically remember the time of the movement.
Although several elite Khmer Rouge have maintained their local government position in exchange for their weapons, their position remains weak, as unqualified farmers.
“These people had only minimal benefit from surrender,” said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which runs public forums across Cambodia, including Anlong Vengu.
“They are surrounded by the utopian agrarian ideology of the regime.”
