Sports and circumvention of rules
Finty, as shown by Alonso and Ramos in a match with Ajax, shows the wit rather than the intention to escape punishment.
The alleged exclusion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the Champions League match against Ajax on November 23 has caused the sea of ink to be written about whether or not this is non-sporting behavior, and whether or not UEFA should be able to state both footballers.
As is known, a few minutes before the end of the match (which had their team clearly won) the named players one by one deliberately lost time at the moment when the foul was to be played to provoke the referee, and he showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, both players will meet the prescribed penalty in the next match against Auxerre - with Real Madrid finishing in their group lead - and will be able to, stripped of cards, continue to the next stage.
In the end, UEFA's disciplinary committee awarded coach José Mourinho a two-game penalty and the guilty players were fined.
Provoking the yellow card under similar conditions is not a new practice, but is more or less common in football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethic of football, i.e. rules that are unwritten but are followed.
Part of the discussion in this case was due to the fact that its participant was the Real Madrid team (which boasts of nobility and honor in its anthem, and which has already penalized its players for similar acts), and apparently also thanks to the dramatization led by Mourinho, who thus adds to his long history of the comedian and provocateur.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of conduct, which is not expressly prohibited by the rules, is contrary to the principles of sport, i.e. whether these acts circumvent the law; it is indeed an action respecting the rules of sport, which, of course, may make sense.
It is decided what type of damage such actions cause to the sports spirit.
One of the necessities of sporting behavior is the physical inviolability of opponents, which has not been violated in these cases, that is, there has not been a violent game.
Another of these necessities that characterize a clean game is to avoid players having an advantage over the opponent's team due to their offense - which is not the case here.
So the paradox of Real Madrid players’ action is that what we normally characterize as a deception or circumvention of the law did not occur, there was no hidden violation of the rules in order to avoid sanctions, but this behavior should be as visible as possible in order to receive the punishment.
They waited and liked to be punished.
The next question, however, is what advantage the perpetrators of their intentional transgression will have.
Here it is necessary to note that the opponent does not get into a disadvantaged position, and that in the current match there is no benefit, because the obvious consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
Nor is it a useful strategy for the next game, as the club will not be able to count on these players.
The advantage obviously lies in the fact that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could jeopardize their participation in the future match.
However, this is an advantage from a long-term perspective and with a certain degree of uncertainty, that is, at first glance, the team can be eliminated, and in addition to this action, the players will refuse the penalty, and move to the second round of cards, in which it is enough to exclude one card less than in the first round.
So as the bikes continue, it is not entirely clear whether this is an advantage.
In short, these actions do not go against the sporting spirit, part of which is to make strategic decisions that will allow you to get the maximum benefit within the rules.
In the case we are dealing with here, the players were not intended to avoid punishment (which would be a clear case of circumvention of the rules), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made strategic decisions without escaping punishment or running away from it.
Although the line between cunning and circumventing the rules is not quite clear, I believe that it was clearly a cunning in this case.
It seems to me that the controversy arises for two reasons: because they were two self-exclusions and because of the way in which the instructions for provoking them from the leadership were transmitted.
Damage to sporting principles by these actions is not as ethical as it is aesthetic.
