The United States changes the rules for granting visas
People will have to turn to the Service Centres for visa applicants before interviewing the Consular Department; the costs will be lower and the waiting time will be shortened.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa negotiation process at the U.S. embassies and consulates will change.
With the new procedure, most applicants will have to contact the Visa Services Centres (abbreviated from the English ASC) before interviewing the Consular Department.
ASC staff will collect the biometric information of the applicant and it will be evaluated by the Consular Department before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including the following:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, you will no longer have to pay a fee for the appointment, the second for the processing of the application and the other for the delivery of the document by the transport service.
The applicant will pay only one fee covering all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: an amount equivalent to $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa applications (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for a visa for merchants and investors.
People who want to renew their visa will not have to interview a consular official, but will only contact the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
Since biometric information will be taken from the ASC, applicants who will require a second meeting with an interview at the Consular Department will spend less time there than in the past.
Similarly, those who apply for a visa at the consulates in Ciudad Ju<0xC3><0xA1>rez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an additional $26 service fee.
For more information on the new procedure for applying for a visa, visit the following website http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
