World Plan for the Restoration of Lighting
In Canc<0xC3><0xBA>n, the United Nations has proposed a plan to restore home lighting, retail lighting and industrial spaces in 100 countries to achieve greenhouse gas (GHG) reductions, which correspond to almost one-third of the additional limit that needs to be achieved to stabilize the planet’s climate from 2020 onwards.
This ambitious plan is at the stage of major concrete projects that the UN wants to implement in Canc<0xC3><0xBA>n to compensate for the absence of difficult-to-implement reduction commitments on the part of industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs, which monopolize another 50 to 70% of the market, were replaced by fluo-compact bulbs or, even better, bulbs with electroluminescent diodes (DELs or "LEDs" in English), a substantial amount from 1.8 billion e.m. to Gt would be replaced by GES.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
That’s the equivalent of 70% of global fleet emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, large countries with a significant share of emissions such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, were involved in voluntary reduction plans that should allow global GHG emissions to fall from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to subtract another 5 Gt from this balance to achieve by 2020 stabilization of warming to 2 degrees Celsius to rule out not getting out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dispersed in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, is the product of light.
With fluo-compact bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with new LED bulbs, we reduce this consumption by two more times.
Fluocompact bulbs last on average from 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, which Philips introduced this week into production – this company allegedly participated in a UN study – have an estimated life of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a lighted bulb, giving us an idea of a possible savings with a land-recovery plan that would apply in the next 100 years.
All of these new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit less heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluocompact bulbs because they contain mercury and need to be classified as hazardous waste, which is still not possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers set up collection plants.
However, according to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not a fluo-compact bulb, but rather a thermal coal-fired power plant, which emits a lot of mercury needed to produce electricity wasted in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants produce 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report also details the gains that each country would make from this international programme.
Indonesia, for example, would save $1 billion a year to buy electricity and $8 million tonnes of CO2, equivalent to 3.5 thermal power plants, which would cost $2.5 billion to build.
