The same applies to secret documents.
The informant is lazy, and the lazy (or limited spirit) head of the secret service (and if he is not, he could be, as I know, the editor of the newspaper Libération) who considers only what he himself admits to be true.
The high-secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. embassy sent to the state prosecutor’s office was the same information that Newsweek had published a week earlier.
So why is there so much turmoil around the disclosure of these documents?
On the one hand, they say what every cultivated person already knows, namely that the embassy, at least since the end of World War II and since the heads of state can telephone or fly off for a joint dinner, has lost its diplomatic function and, except for a few small exercises in the transformation of the center.
Any viewer who watches the investigative films knows very well that it is only out of licentiousness that he seemingly ignores it.
However, the fact that it is repeated publicly defames the duty of hypocrisy and throws a bad light on American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can obtain the most highly classified information from the most powerful country in the world represents a hard blow, not negligible, to the prestige of this state court.
The scandal affects both the victims and their "performers".
But let's move from here to the deep truth about what happened.
Once upon a time, in Orwell’s time, it was possible to grasp all the power, like some Big Brother who controlled every movement of his people.
Orvell’s prophecy has been proven ever since, that by being able to control every movement through the phone, every transaction made, every hotel visited, the highway used, and so on, a citizen became a complete victim of the wreath of power.
But when we demonstrate how things are going now, that even the “graves” with the most secret information of the powerful cannot withstand the intervention of any hacker, the control message ceases to be one-way and becomes a circulation.
Power is controlled by every citizen, but every citizen, or at least a hacker – elected as a citizen’s avenger – can know all the secrets of power.
How can one keep a power that no longer has the power to keep its own secrets?
It is true that Georg Simmel has already said that the real secret is a non-content secret (and the non-content secret can never be revealed by him); it is also true that all information about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed a mysterious non-content secret, because it is a non-content secret, because it is a non-content secret, as he has extracted it from the public life.
WikiLeaks made no mistake about Sarkozy or Merkel, but it did something big for Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound inflicted on such a great power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will not be able to send sensitive information online - this would amount to its publication on a poster glued to the corner of the street.
But it is also quite obvious that with current technologies, it is useless to hope that you can keep a message secret over the phone.
There is nothing easier than to find out if and when the head of state traveled by plane and connected with one of his colleagues.
How will private and sensitive news be kept secret in the future?
I know that for the moment my forecast belongs to sci-fi and is fantastic, but I have to imagine the government factors that transport discreetly the fulfillment of formalities on uncontrollable routes and carry with them only those messages that know from memory or rather hide the rare information in the booth.
The information will be kept in unique copies in key-closed drawers: overall, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
