Climate: How France hacked its funding promises
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to try to keep promises for fast-start (or early-start) financing implemented by developed countries.
And big French hacks were uncovered
Under the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries committed to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union pledged <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion for three years and France <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.26 billion (i.e. 420 million per year).
At the start of COP16, the EU drew a big ace to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: a report clarifying the action of its member states, a press conference, a grand side event, distribution of brochures...
A transparent operation invaluable and valued for its real value: advanced countries and civil society would like to see all advanced countries and civil society do the same and with the same degree of accuracy.
The EU announces that it released <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion in 2010, which puts it on track to meet its pledge of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we focus on the detail, we find that things are much more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, these funds are "new and additional" to ensure that the increased burden is realised without detriment to Public Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission has proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 to be a reference year: international funding has remained and it adds another 150 million for the three-year title of fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment deadlines or with deadlines at the level of public development assistance.
On the other hand, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous periods or to the global level of Public Aid for Development d'Aide publique au développement.
Specifically, the total amount of France’s support to developing countries may remain unchanged (or even decrease), it has to comply with its commitment to finance “new and additional”...
Another crucial element is the division into gifts and loans.
There is no rule yet and everyone chooses their own method of calculation.
Some, such as France, think that 1<0xE2><0x82><0xAC> borrowed is equal to 1<0xE2><0x82><0xAC> donated.
Obviously, this is difficult to prove: effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be proved for some investments that are profitable (often it is projects associated with reducing emissions, consisting of more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro that we get as the equivalent of one euro that we give... , but we should not understand it from the point of view of our own.
But France can only give the following justification: it "observes" its commitment of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million, of which it makes 91.5% of the loan (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>389.8 million) and 8.5% of the donations (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>36.1 million) - see the EU document to verify this for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union that uses the loan on such a scale.
Germany claimed 46% of the money, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) fulfilled their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the absolute majority of the European Union gives <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1 to fulfill its promise, it gives France only 10 cents and considers this effort comparable.
That's a beautiful piece of walrus!
In summary, in its "fast start" financing, France operates with double hedging: on the one hand, with the development of the stock in time and on the other with a real financial burden.
Although it spends only <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>36.1 million, it can convince that it spends <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million "new and additional" in connection with its promises.
The manipulation of the finance minister (because it seems that although Bercy made such decisions) could have a double negative impact, at the same time within the EU (why would Member States continue to donate when it is enough to lend?) and in negotiations, because developing countries are not completely naive...
The chapter on early funding is only a small question, relatively short-term, in relation to a series of climate debates.
But it could be a grain of sand extra in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope this isn't our case.
Whatever it is, it is necessary to draw on the knowledge from this first year of early funding.
First, France should announce a change in its way of keeping records for 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of respecting its obligations and of decency and fairness vis-<0xC3><0xA0>-vis the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France should avoid discussions on long-term financing deposits (another key chapter currently under discussion): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or how to account for loans.
France should change its stance to become as progressive with these deposits as with the others.
All hope is therefore placed in the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will come to Cancun next week.
The surprising announcement of France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans could lead to an increase in the level of international confidence necessary to move forward in the discussions.
The alarm about pesticides that children consume.
A 10-year-old child will consume 81 different chemicals one day, according to one study published this Wednesday, from the Future Generations Association (ex- Movement for the Rights and Preservation of Future Generations).
The association, which notes that its results "do not have a significant statistical value with regard to the low number of samples analyzed, but are characteristic of the processed issue," bought between July and September foods commonly consumed in four meals and one light meal as a light snack per child in about a decade.
These typical dishes, including official recommendations – five pieces of fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day – as well as sweets, were analyzed by research laboratories on chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are among the carcinogens, possible or probable, and five substances are among the clear carcinogens, as well as 37 substances that could act as an interfering center for glands with internal mixing (PE), according to studies.
"Although in almost all cases the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, in our research we see well that the reality in consumer exposure to contaminants, perhaps carcinogens, and/or PE is striking," the association said.
For breakfast, butter and tea with milk contain about ten residues with possible carcinogenic effects and three proven to be certain carcinogens, as are about twenty residues that could disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, reported by studies as a small snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to green beans from Kenya, included in the lunch, in which studies have found traces of strong insecticides banned in the EU.
In addition, minced meat steaks, canned tuna and even ham and gum were sprayed with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the water from the faucet analysis revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
The steak from the salmon for dinner was “the richest” with 34 chemical residues discovered, and even the analysis of a plastic plate used to heat food in the microwave did not escape the analysis.
The ultimate risk to consumers of this “contaminant cocktail” is likely underestimated,” the study concludes.
The Ecological Europe-Greens Association (EE-LV) has proposed a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop the "growth of civilisational diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) examined the status of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, 76 of them in cereals.
